{[show NS]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \D4. From your \DQJ643 the four is fourth-best from your longest suit, a sound length lead against their spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
I am in 4\S and counting losers: with both top trumps and a strong club suit, my only weakness is hearts, where my \HQ954 face dummy's singleton \HJ - and the dummy trumps give me a way out, holding me to just two losers and a cushion. The plan is to ruff hearts in dummy, the short trump hand, BEFORE drawing all the trumps, using dummy's trumps while they last. NS hold 26 of the 40 points, the defenders share only 14, and since neither one bid, no one is concealing a long suit or extra strength.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \D4; the card is a fact, its meaning a guess - it looks like fourth-best from length, but I will let the play confirm it. I win the diamond, and before pulling all the trumps I lead a heart toward dummy and ruff it with a dummy trump, then return and ruff a second heart in dummy, taking heart losers off with the short hand's trumps. After the ruffs I draw the remaining trumps and run my clubs, conceding only what the defenders are owed. With the ruffs in early the hand comes to eleven tricks, one more than I need.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The key was ruffing the hearts in dummy's short trump hand before drawing trumps - clear them early and the ruffing tricks go with them. You read the loser count and timed the ruffs well for all eleven tricks. Lovely work.}
